As a local, I rarely eat out, as most local dishes are best cooked at home, but I relented and went to Gumbo Ya-Ya to meet some out-of-towners. While I stand by my assertion that home cooking is the *best*, I will acknowledge that Gumbo Ya-Ya was pretty darn good, and they weren't excessively expensive, particularly given their location. I liked that they had an option to choose three dishes to receive smaller portions of, as our visitors were only in town for a short while and wanted to try as much as possible at once. I probably wouldn't go again unless I had visitors and didn't feel like cooking, but if you're a tourist or just a local who can't cook, I would actually recommend them!

(Visited 5/26/2019) This restaurant is located in the French Quarter, walking distance from our hotel room. We arrived for lunch and the host told us there was a 20min wait. We waited for about 15 minutes outside in the patio area before we were seated. Once inside, several patrons were shocked to observe so many empty tables and didn't understand the need for the wait. Anyway, our server was attentive and friendly. We started with beignets stuffed with andouille sausage. They were slightly overcooked (batter was a little too crunchy), but they tasted delicious, especially when eaten with syrup! I ordered the traditional red beans n rice (which comes with a sausage link and buttermilk fried chicken tenders) and shrimp and grits. Everything tasted great, and the portions were plenty. I will definitely return to this establishment on my next trip to The Big Easy.
